{% set L = ctx.law_stats %}The workflow ran in four stages, each reported in its own section below. First, Asta's [AutoDiscovery](#sec-reproduction) searched the source cohort and surfaced **{{ L.n }} surprising candidate hypotheses**{% if ctx.run_id %} (run `{{ ctx.run_id }}`){% endif %}. Second, Asta's [Paper Finder](#sec-literature) assembled the grounding literature (**{{ ctx.ref_papers|length }} papers** across **{{ ctx.lit_themes|length }} themes**). {% set R = ctx.repro_stats %}Third, Asta's [DataVoyager](#sec-reproduction) re-tested the hypotheses on {{ ctx.datasets|length }} independent dataset{{ '' if ctx.datasets|length == 1 else 's' }}, with a significance-based verdict: **{{ R.supported }} supported** and {{ R.supported_partial }} partially supported on independent data, {{ R.opposite_effect }} showed a significant opposite effect, and {{ R.rejected }} were rejected as adequately powered nulls; the remaining {{ R.inconclusive }} were inconclusive (underpowered) and {{ R.not_tested }} could not be tested. Fourth, Asta's [Theorizer](#sec-theories) generated **{{ ctx.n_theories }} literature-grounded theories** under {{ ctx.objectives|length }} objectives ({{ ctx.objectives|map('replace','_focused','')|join(' and ') }}), of which **{{ ctx.n_testable_theories }}** {{ 'is' if ctx.n_testable_theories == 1 else 'are' }} testable on the data in hand. The appendix expands every entity in the reverse order, theories first and the per-node reproductions last.
